//
// test/Lower/m3_corpus/s28/pass.test — M5 T106 / FR-030 / SC-003.
//
// **Cross-milestone deferral (M5+ visitor infra).** NSL syntax places
// `state s1 { ... }` definitions at module top-level (sibling of
// `proc p`); M4's frozen 79-op dialect placed `nsl.state` under
// `HasParent<"ProcOp">`. The visitor must therefore map each top-
// level state-defn to the proc(s) that reference it via
// `state_name s1, s2;` — a per-proc `controlTable_`/`nameTable_`
// inversion that exceeds the M5 visitor's current scope. Multi-proc
// state-name sharing further complicates: two procs referencing the
// same state name cannot both host an `nsl.state @s1` (Symbol
// uniqueness). The eventual fix is M5+ visitor work, possibly
// alongside an M4 amendment relaxing `nsl.state`'s parent constraint.
//
// XFAIL: *
// RUN: %nslc -emit=mlir %S/../../../sema/s28/pass.nsl > %t.actual.mlir
